Titanic dataset

## Loading required package: ggplot2

Now we use ggplot2 to visualise the data, and specifically related to survival. First and foremost, what was the survival rate?

ggplot(titanic, aes(x = Survived)) +
  geom_bar() +
  theme_bw() + 
  labs(y = "Passanger Count", title = "Titanic Survival rates")

Most people perished on the titanic.

Secondly, what was the survival rate by gender?

ggplot(titanic, aes(x = Sex, fill = Survived)) +
  geom_bar() +
  theme_bw() + 
  labs(y = "Passanger Count", title = "Titanic Survival rates by sex")

As expected, disproportionately more women survived than men.

Thirdly, what was the survival rate by ticket class?

ggplot(titanic, aes(x = Pclass, fill = Survived)) +
  geom_bar() +
  theme_bw() + 
  labs(x = "Ticket class",
    y = "Passanger Count", title = "Titanic Survival rates by ticket class")

Most people in third class, i.e. the cheapest tickets, and in first class, more than half survived, men and women. Also, interestingly enough, from this chart we see that 3rd class tickets were sold the most, approx. 500, as expected, however second class tickets were sold less than first class.

Next we will see out of the passenger ticket class, how many of the survived where women and how many were men.

ggplot(titanic, aes(x = Sex, fill = Survived)) +
  geom_bar() +
  facet_wrap(~ Pclass) +
  theme_bw() + 
  labs(x = "Ticket class",
    y = "Passanger Count", title = "Titanic Survival rates by ticket class and sex")

As expected, women survived in each class disproportionately more than men, where men survived the most in first class, and females in first and second class overwhelmingly survived, whereas in third, only about half survived.

Now we analyse age and its impact on survival rates.

ggplot(titanic, aes(x = Age, fill = Survived)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5) +
  facet_wrap(~ Sex) +
  theme_bw() + 
  labs(x = "Age",
    y = "Passanger Count", title = "Titanic age distribution of survived")
## Warning: Removed 177 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

We see that a huge chunk of the passengers fall between 20 and 40 years of age. We also see that there were some children, and even older folks (over 80) in a time where life expectancy wasn’t that high. Next, we see that that children, especially at the younger end, disproportionately survived, whereas for older people, survivability was quite low. And lastly, as mentioned before, women survived much more disproportionately than men.

Finally, we could create a density plot to see survival rate of population based on gender, age and class ticket.

ggplot(titanic, aes(x = Age, fill = Survived)) +
  facet_wrap(Sex ~ Pclass) +
  theme_bw() + 
  geom_density(alpha = 0.5) +

  labs(x = "Ticket class",
    y = "Passanger Count", title = "Titanic Survival rates by ticket class, age and sex")
